I meant it like this:
```c
///// export /////
static int func(int x);

///// proto /////
static int func_used_by_other_utility_code(double y);/*proto*/

///// impl /////
static int func(int x) { /*...*/ }
static int func_used_by_other_utility_code(double y) { /* ... */ }
```
This utility code would generate this C code when _not_ using a shared module:
```c
/* proto section */
static int func(int x); /*proto*/
static int func_used_by_other_utility_code(double y);/*proto*/

/* ........... */
/* utiltiy code impls */
static int func(int x) { /*...*/ }
static int func_used_by_other_utility_code(double y) { /* ... */ }
```
And when using a shared module, it would generate the same code inside of the shared module, and just this code inside of the user module that imports the shared module:
```c
/* proto section */
static int (*func)(int x);
```
Here, we'd explicitly list both the exported functions and types for the shared module, and the predeclared functions/types that just needs to show up early because other utility code uses it.

